observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Municipal Mayor instruct the GAD Focal Point System to:
a) review and update the GAD Code in accordance with the guidelines prescribed by PCW; 
b) exert more effort to complete its sex-disaggregated data in order to address the real issue on the PPAs in the GAD Plan and Budget (GPB) and finally institutionalize its GAD database; 
c) use a gender monitoring tool like HGDG on the attributed budget to evaluate gender responsiveness of PPAs in the GBP; 
d) conduct a training program on the use of the HGDG tool to GAD employees to deepen their understanding of the use of the HGDG in its GPB; and 
e) ensure complete and timely implementation of GAD PPAs so that desired results and benefits for the intended recipients/beneficiaries are fully achieved.

We recommended and Management agreed to consider the following remedial measures; to wit:
a) instruct the Municipal Accountant to (1) exert diligent effort to trace the source of prior years’ unaccounted balance of Land account totaling ₱232,035.11; (2) draw JEVs taking up the recognition of (i) assets procured out of TF under the appropriate Assets accounts in the GF books; (ii) depreciation expenses for completed infrastructure project and PPEs purchased out of TF; and (iii) dropping of obsolete properties from the books upon disposal; (3) update the PPELC for all property accounts to support the recorded balances of PPE; and (4) henceforth, ensure that the infrastructure projects are recorded to appropriate Asset accounts upon completion;
b) direct the Property Custodian to (i) maintain complete and updated property cards per category of PPE; and (ii) identify all unserviceable properties for disposal and initiate the disposal of unserviceable properties to realize additional income therefrom for the benefit of the Municipality; and
c) instruct the Municipal Assessor and Property Custodian to ascertain the status of other parcels of land owned by the Municipality with titling issues and facilitate the titling thereof in the name of the LGU to warrant the absolute and clear ownership;
d) create an Inventory Committee who shall (i) conduct complete physical count of PPE; and (ii) prepare the corresponding RPCPPE with appropriate remarks on the condition and whereabouts of the PPE; and
e) form a Disposal Committee who shall perform the immediate disposal all properties unserviceable and unusable office/other supplies and equipment using appropriate mode of disposal, as determined and recommended by the Committee, to avoid further deterioration and earn income from the sale thereof, if warranted.

We recommended that management instruct the Municipal Treasurer to 

intensify collections by undertaking effective revenue collection strategies such as periodic sending of notice of delinquencies and tax bills by personal or mail service and coordination with barangay officials and national and local offices that have access to the addresses of delinquent taxpayers; 

avail of all legal and administrative remedies allowed under R.A. No. 7160; 

submit the certified list of taxpayers and the amount of taxes due to the Municipal Accountant; and 



(iv) maintain a close coordination with the Municipal Assessor as regards the newly assessed real properties.

We recommended that management:

prioritize proper maintenance of the Municipal MRF as well as the repair of the unserviceable machineries, equipment and vehicles and consider purchasing additional units to cope with the collection, transport and disposal of solid wastes; 

immediately facilitate the dumping of solid wastes piled up at the MRF after entering into a contract on the hiring of services for the Sanitary Landfill facility. Submit a copy of the said contract and all supporting documents thereto to the Auditor’s Office within five days from execution pursuant to Section 3.1 of COA Circular No. 2009-001;

intensify the information and education campaign to the barangays, particularly the proper maintenance of their MRFs and prohibition of open burning of solid wastes; 



expedite the process of promulgation of local ordinance prohibiting littering as well as the open burning of solid wastes like hay stalks, dried leaves and other farm wastes and set fines and penalties against violators; and

instruct the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to strictly comply with the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of R. A. No, 9184 to ensure that all procurements even those minimal in amounts are conducted in a manner that would be most advantageous to the Municipality.

We recommended that management:

carefully plan on how to achieve the ideal and realistic number of personnel complement of the Municipality; consider filling up funded vacant permanent positions to resolve the problem on lack of personnel; and decide on re-hiring job order/contractual personnel only when the circumstances warrant, based on actual project/program needs;

instruct the Human Resource Designate/ Human Resource Assistant to

strictly monitor attendance of job order personnel by ensuring their truthful compliance in filling out logbooks of daily attendance and DTRs; 



analyze/evaluate workload of each office and prepare a more organized staffing pattern; 

stop granting overtime pay to JO personnel; and 



(iv) submit all the documents filed with HR as regards the hiring of JOs for our verification; and



instruct Department Heads to verify/certify DTRs as to prescribed office hours prior to endorsement of the same to the Municipal Mayor for approval/signature.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the:

a.	Municipal Budget Officer to appropriate and set aside not less than 5% of the estimated revenue from regular sources for MDRRMF;

b. 	MDRRMO to (i) monitor and evaluate the utilization of MDRRMF based on the programs, projects and activities listed in the Work and Financial Plan; 



 (ii) ensure compliance with the prescribed minimum standards for disaster preparedness developed by the DILG and LGA; 



(iii) ensure that the fund intended for post-disaster activities are used in accordance with the provisions of NDRRMC-DBM-DILG Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-1; and



(iv) furnish the Office of the Auditor with Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF in the required format through the LDRRMC and Local Development Council on or before the 15th day after the end of each month; and 



c. 	Municipal Accountant to (i) perform a thorough review of all disbursement claims to ensure that these are properly supported with complete documentation and proper approval by authorized officials/ representatives; and (ii) ensure that succeeding transactions have been properly recorded to appropriate expense accounts.

We recommended that management instruct the: 

Local School Board to judiciously plan the priority PPAs to be included in the LSB Plan and Budget to avoid several realignment of funds;

Municipal Accountant/Municipal Treasurer to (i) submit explanation on the discrepancies noted on the procurement documents, as summarized in Appendix K; and (ii) combine efforts to submit immediately the lacking documents enumerated in Appendix L; 

Prepare necessary adjusting entries to correct the erroneous recording of the purchase uniforms amounting to ₱32,080.25 by debiting Other Supplies and Materials Expense and crediting Food Supplies Expenses; and

Municipal Accountant to ensure that succeeding disbursements charged against the Fund are properly supported with complete documentation to avoid incurrence of audit suspensions/
disallowances.

We recommended that management:

a. 	prioritize the repair of the unserviceable machineries, equipment and vehicles and consider purchasing additional units to cope with the collection, transport and disposal of solid wastes; 

b. 	continuously educate the constituents, particularly the market vendors, on the proper waste segregation and implement the “No segregation, no collection policy” more strictly;

c. 	intensify the information and education campaign to stop totally the open burning of solid wastes, particularly in the rural and remote areas; and 


d. 	expedite the process of promulgation of local ordinance prohibiting the open burning of solid wastes like hay stalks, dried leaves and other farm wastes and set fines and penalties for violators.

We recommended that management: 

a. 	ensure that GAD information are reliable, such as gender statistics and sex-disaggregated data, which shall serve as valuable inputs for planning, budgeting, programming, and policy formulation for the set up and maintenance of GAD database; 



b. 	observe strictly the timelines for the preparation and submission of GAD Plan and Budget and the corresponding GAD Accomplishment Report to ensure timely and relevant plan, proper implementation thereof, and effective evaluation of the PPAs; 

c. 	instruct the GAD Focal Person to facilitate the submission of GAD Accomplishment Report which is vital in the generation of succeeding year’s plan and budget; and



d. 	issue an Executive Order for the establishment of GAD Monitoring and Evaluation Team that will evaluate the results of the LGU GAD policies, programs, and projects.

We recommended that management:
ensure that GAD information are reliable, such as gender statistics and sex-disaggregated data, which shall serve as valuable inputs for planning, budgeting, programming, and policy formulation for the set up and maintenance of GAD database;
observe strictly the timelines for the preparation and submission of GAD Plan and Budget and the corresponding GAD Accomplishment Report to ensure timely and relevant plan, proper implementation thereof, and effective evaluation of the PPAs;
instruct the GAD Focal Person to facilitate the submission of GAD Accomplishment Report which is vital in the generation of succeeding year’s plan and budget; and
issue an Executive Order for the establishment of GAD Monitoring and Evaluation Team that will evaluate the results of the LGU GAD policies, programs, and projects.
The Municipal Mayor commented that the GAD Focal Person is currently consolidating the accomplishment report from different departments for CY 2018. On the other hand, the GAD Plan and Budget for CY 2020 was already submitted to DILG for approval.

We recommended and management agreed to:

conduct a thorough review and analysis of all outstanding payables to National Government Agencies, Government Owned and Controlled Corporations and Local Government Units;

review and monitor all booked obligations to ensure that only valid claims remain in the books; 

maintain and update regularly the subsidiary ledgers complete with the necessary details on the accounts;

effect the proper liquidation to the concerned agencies and remit the remaining balances of the funds downloaded after the completion of the project unless not required to be returned to the trustor; and

record the necessary adjusting entries to reclassify to their proper accounts all misclassified transactions.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the:

MDRRM Council to monitor and evaluate the utilization of MDRRMF based on the programs, projects and activities listed in the Work and Financial Plan;

concerned personnel to facilitate the hiring of an MDRRMO and three staff who will assist the MDRRMO to ensure and pursue the full implementation of the pre-disaster preparedness programs;


Municipal Accountant to perform a thorough review of all disbursement claims to ensure that these are properly supported with complete documentation and proper approval by authorized officials/
representatives. Submit the documents required for the deficient disbursements totaling to ₱1,196,534.94 to avoid issuance of Notice of Suspension (NS);

furnish the Office of the Auditor with Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF in the required format through the LDRRMC and Local Development Council on or before the 15th day after the end of each month; and

Municipal Budget Officer to comply with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2012-002 in establishing Registry of Appropriations, Allotments and Obligations for Quick Response Fund, Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund - Maintenance and Other Operating Expenses, Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund - Capital Outlay for proper monitoring of funds and to establish the correct balance to be transferred to the Special Trust Fund.

We recommended and management agreed to:

ensure that waste segregators are properly equipped with personal protective equipment to protect them from hazards of handling solid wastes;

intensify the information campaign on “No Segregation, No Collection Policy” and encourage the active participation of constituents particularly the market vendors and commercial/business establishments in the proper waste disposal from source;


consider purchasing additional machinery, equipment and vehicle to cope with the collection, transport and disposal of solid wastes; and




undertake proper information dissemination like conduct of seminars, production of posters/tarpaulins on the harmful effects to public health of the smoke from burned solid wastes; and solicit the assistance of the Sanggunian in the promulgation of local ordinance prohibiting the open burning of solid wastes like hay stalks, dried leaves and other farm wastes and set fines and penalties for violators.

We recommended that management instruct the Municipal Accountant to:  

ensure that all taxes withheld from employees as well as from suppliers/contractors are immediately remitted to the BIR within the prescribed period; 

supervise closely the Accounting staff in charge of the analysis of the unremitted balance of prior years and cause the immediate remittance thereof to the BIR;

submit justification for the transfer of unremitted taxes under the General Fund amounting to ₱216,877.87 from Due to BIR to Other Payables account; and 

exercise extra care in the recording of transactions to ensure accuracy of ledger balances of the Due to BIR account per fund.

We reiterated our previous year’s audit recommendations that the Local Chief Executive:

require the Municipal Treasurer to: (i) implement aggressive collection strategies to enforce collection of delinquent accounts; 



(ii) regularly send notices/demand letters to all delinquent stallholders to promptly settle their accounts in order to avoid possible distraint of goods, chattels, or effects, and other personal property; 

(iii) enforce the cancellation of the lease and forfeit in favor of the Municipality any and all improvements found in the stalls of the delinquent lessees; 


(iv) regularly furnish the Municipal Accountant with list of collectibles from delinquent stallholders/lessees as basis of recording; and 


instruct the Municipal Accountant to recognize the rental receivables arising from all unpaid market stalls and Municipal-owned buildings.

