8.13	We recommended and management agreed to:
ensure that waste segregators are properly equipped with personal protective equipment to protect them from hazards of handling solid wastes;
intensify the information campaign on “No Segregation, No Collection Policy” and encourage the active participation of constituents particularly the market vendors and commercial/business establishments in the proper waste disposal from source;
consider purchasing additional machinery, equipment and vehicle to cope with the collection, transport and disposal of solid wastes; and
undertake proper information dissemination like conduct of seminars, production of posters/tarpaulins on the harmful effects to public health of the smoke from burned solid wastes; and solicit the assistance of the Sanggunian in the promulgation of local ordinance prohibiting the open burning of solid wastes like hay stalks, dried leaves and other farm wastes and set fines and penalties for violators.

We recommended that management:

mobilize additional competent personnel from other departments to facilitate the completion of the physical inventory of all properties owned by the Municipality and report the results thereof using the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE); 

require the Municipal Treasurer to exert possible remedies in locating the Acknowledgement Receipt for Equipment (ARE) issued in prior years and ensure the issuance/renewal of corresponding ARE or PAR whenever the property is issued to the end-user. This should be regularly updated at least every three years or upon change of property accountability, such as during transfer and return/surrender of property;

instruct the Municipal Accountant to update and reconcile the Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards (PPELC) against the balances recorded in the general ledger; and

advise the Municipal Treasurer to maintain property cards for each class of PPE to be regularly reconciled with the PPELC and other pertinent Accounting records.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant (i) maintain the practice of sending notices or reminders to personnel for the prompt liquidation of their cash advances as soon as the purpose thereof had been accomplished;

(ii) stop the practice of granting new cash advances without the liquidation of previous ones; and

(iii) submit immediately the lacking documents for various transactions post-audited and ensure that liquidation reports are supported with complete documentations.

We recommended that:

the Municipal Treasurer submit a Certified List of Taxpayers with account balances and complete aging schedule of receivables as of December 31, 2016 in accordance with Section 20, Volume I of the New Government Accounting (NGAS) for Local Government Units;

instruct the Municipal Accountant to trace and record the adjustments to reconcile the differences between the amount of the recorded RPT and SET receivables and the related Deferred Credits accounts;

the personnel in-charge in the Municipal Treasurer’s Office regularly update and reconcile her records of delinquencies with the Real Property Tax Account Register/Taxpayer’s index card to report the correct amount of delinquent taxes;

the Municipal Treasurer ensure continuous/proper monitoring of receivables by sending demand letters especially on the delinquent accounts and intensify efforts on the collection drive towards an improved RPT and SET collection efficiency; and

the Municipal Mayor, through the Municipal Treasurer, avail of all legal and administrative remedies either by administrative action through levy on real property or judicial action as provided by Sections 183, 256, 257 to 258 and 270 of the Local Government Code of 1991.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

a.	require the Municipal Treasurer to (i) implement aggressive collection strategies to enforce collection of delinquent accounts;


     (ii) regularly send notices/demand letters to all delinquent stallholders to promptly settle their accounts in order to avoid possible distraint of goods, chattels, or effects, and other personal property;

     (iii) enforce the cancellation of the lease and forfeit in favor of the Municipality, any and all improvements found in the stalls of delinquent lessees; and

     (iv) ensure that all employees performing collection functions are properly bonded; and

b.	instruct the Municipal Accountant to record the rental receivables from all the unpaid market stalls.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

a.	advise the Local Poverty Reduction and Action Team (LPRAT) to closely monitor the projects that were identified and programmed under the Bottom-up Budgeting for their immediate implementation;


b.	cause the execution of a MOA for all fund transfers which shall contain the guidelines and procedures in the implementation of projects by the implementing/recipient LGUs, including their responsibilities; 

c.	instruct the Municipal Accountant to coordinate with the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) for the completion and submission of the documentary deficiencies noted and ensure that disbursement vouchers are supported with complete documentation before payments are made; and 

d.	avoid payment of claims in excess of the allowable amounts/rates.

We reiterated the prior year audit recommendations that the Local Chief Executive (i) instruct the BAC members and the Municipal Engineer to properly plan and schedule all procurement activities pertaining to development projects to pave the way for their timely implementation and completion; 

(ii) ensure that the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator and the Municipal Engineer regularly monitor the status of project implementation so that necessary interventions may be introduced at the earliest time, for instance, deployment of personnel to provide technical and clerical support, thus, facilitating engineering activities; and 

(iii) instruct the Municipal Accountant to cause the immediate submission of the lacking documentary requirements and ensure that only disbursement vouchers with complete documentations are processed and presented for payment to establish proper accountability among certifying/approving agency officials.

We recommended that management:

a. 	maximize the utilization of LDRRMF to ensure the delivery of calamity-related programs, projects and activities. Likewise, consider the procurement of early warning systems, preparedness equipment and other equipage for floods, earthquake, volcanic eruptions, landslide and other natural and man-made calamities out of the 70% Mitigation Fund;

b.  	instruct the Municipal Accountant to perform a thorough review of all disbursement claims to ensure that these are properly supported with complete documentation and proper approval by authorized officials/
      representatives;

c.  	advise the Municipal Budget Officer to include any unexpended balance of DRRMF-CO in the continuing balance under General Fund until the projects are completed and to comply with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2012-002 in establishing Registry of Appropriations, Allotments and Obligations for Quick Response Fund, Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund-Maintenance and Other Operating Expenses, Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund–Capital Outlay for proper monitoring of funds and to establish the correct balance to be transferred to Special Trust Fund. Such balances should be submitted to the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer for recording and issuance of check;

d.  	instruct the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator to include in the LDRRMFIP the list of programs, projects and activities to be undertaken out of the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years; and

e.  	consider the creation of permanent position for LDRRM Officer and hire additional staff to comply with the required three (3) technical staff responsible for administration and training; research and planning; and operations and warning.

We recommended that the management:

a. 	coordinate with the Department of Environment and Natural Resources (DENR) in locating and acquiring a suitable lot for the construction of sanitary landfill and secure Environmental Compliance Certificate (ECC) before operation. Likewise, seek possible assistance from the national government for funding the proposed Sanitary Landfill;

b. 	ensure that waste segregators are equipped with personal protective equipment to free them from hazards of handling solid wastes;



c. 	encourage the active participation of schools, private organizations and the barangay officials in informing and educating households in the proper waste disposal from source;



d. 	consider purchasing additional machinery, equipment and vehicle necessary for the collection, transport and disposal of solid wastes;



e. 	ensure that the existing Materials Recovery Facility (MRF) of the component barangays are fully functional and provide necessary support in enjoining the remaining barangays without MRF to establish their own; 

f. 	prohibit the open burning of solid wastes like hay stalks, dried leaves and other farm wastes to protect air and water from pollution; and

g. 	prioritize the implementation of programs and projects identified in the SWMP and AIP pertaining to solid waste management.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive: 

a.	ensure that at least 5% of the total LGU annual appropriations is allotted to support GAD PAPs; 

b.	see to it that the GAD Focal Point System (GFPS) undertake its function of conducting gender mainstreaming to generate gender-responsive plans and programs;



c.	make sure that GAD information are reliable such as, gender statistics and sex-disaggregated data, which shall serve as inputs for planning, budgeting, programming and policy formulation for the setting up and maintenance of GAD database;


d.	strive for the full implementation of GAD-related PAPs by maximizing the application of available funds for the intended purposes exclusively so that the desired outcomes are attained and benefits are enjoyed to the fullest by the intended beneficiaries; and

e.	evaluate the GAD plan, budget and accomplishments periodically or as frequently as needed to ascertain whether the activities undertaken by the LGU effectively addressed the real gender issues and concerns of men and women within the locality.

We recommended that the:

a. 	Members of the SB consider enacting appropriate ordinance on the regulation of the operations of three-wheeled public conveyances to prevent undesirable outcomes as a result of unregulated proliferation of tricycles along the national highways, which may pose hazards and imminent danger to pedestrians and motorists’ lives and properties and impede the flow of traffic;

b. 	implement stricter collection system on the payment of franchise and other fees and consider imposing higher penalty to deter increase of violations; 



c. 	Municipal Human Resource Officer consider the necessity of hiring additional traffic enforcers assigned in two-shifts, that would apprehend and impose fines and penalties to traffic violators; and

d. 	consider installing Closed Circuit Televisions (CCTVs) to monitor the situation in the locality including safety and traffic conditions in major thoroughfares within the Municipality; facilitate tracking and investigation of violators; and provide legislators (SB) with situational updates for improving existing ordinances.

We recommended that the management:

instruct the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards against the balances recorded in the general ledger and the Municipal Treasurer to maintain property cards for each class of PPE; 

require the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to update and reconcile their records regularly;

require the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to conduct detailed and complete physical inventory of all properties owned by the LGU and record the same using the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE); and

require the Municipal Treasurer to issue Acknowledge-ment Receipt for Equipment whenever property is issued to the end-user and this should be regularly updated at least every 3 years or upon change of property accountability such as during transfer and return/surrender of property.

We recommended that the management:

minimize the travelling cost incurred relative to the attendance in seminars by choosing the most economical and informative seminar offered within or outside the region; 

refrain from attending practically similar seminar; 

ensure that each participant attend only in seminars/ trainings within their field of specialization or relative to their current duties and responsibilities; and

conduct every meetings of municipal officials and employees within the premises/offices of the municipality or other less expensive venue located within the locality.

We recommended that management:

consider the creation of permanent position for LDRRM Officer and three technical staff responsible for administration and training; research and planning; and operations and warning;    

instruct the Municipal Accountant to perform a thorough review of each voucher to ensure that disbursements are  properly supported with complete documentation and to draw an entry for the transfer of the unexpended balance of QRF and DRRM-MOOE to the  Special Trust Fund based on the submitted balances of the Municipal Budget copy furnished the Municipal Treasurer for the issuance of check;

instruct the Municipal Treasurer to secure a copy of certified balances of unexpended balance of QRF and DRRMF-MOOE to the Municipal Budget for the issuance of check;

advise the Municipal Budget Officer to include any unexpended balance of DRRMF-CO in the continuing balance under General Fund until the projects are completed and to comply with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2012-002 in establishing Registry of Appropriations, Allotments and Obligations for Quick Response Fund, Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund-Maintenance and Other Operating Expenses, Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund –Capital Outlay for proper monitoring of funds and to establish the correct balance to be transferred to Special Trust Fund. These balances should be submitted to the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer for recording and issuance of check; and

consider the procurement of early warning systems, preparedness equipment and other equipage for floods, earthquake, volcanic eruptions, landslide and other natural and man-made calamities out of the 70% Mitigation Fund.

We recommended that the management:

coordinate with the Department of Environment and Natural Resources (DENR) in locating and acquiring a suitable lot for the construction of sanitary landfill and secure Environmental Compliance Certificate (ECC) before operation;



coordinate with the barangay officials in the establishment and operation of Materials Recovery Facility (MRF) within the barangay and adhere to the rules and regulations provided under Sections 32 of R.A. No. 9003; 

seek financial assistance from the national government for funding the proposed Sanitary Landfill, the construction of Material Recovery Facility including the rehabilitation of damaged MRF and the provision of machines;

encourage the active participation of schools, private organizations and the barangay officials in informing and educating households in the proper waste disposal from source;



pass an ordinance for “no segregation, no collection policy" and this must be strictly enforced; 



prioritize the implementation of programs identified in the SWMP and the environmental programs under the 20% Development Fund pertaining to solid waste management; and



refrain from authorizing and sending job order employees to seminar pursuant to CSC Resolution No. 02-0790 dated June 05, 2002.
